<chapter id=getting-help>Getting Help
<newline>&empty;<newline>
	<idx>getting help<\idx>
	<idx>online help<\idx>
	<idx>Help Manager<\idx>
	<idx>help: key<\idx>
	<idx>help: menu<\idx>
	<idx>help: browsing<\idx>
	<idx>browsing help volumes<\idx>
	<idx>help: button<\idx>
	
Here are the ways you can request help:

<list bullet tight>
 <item> <link help-key>Press F1 or the Help key<\link>
 <item> <link help-menu>Choose an item from the Help menu<\link>
 <item> <link help-button>Click the Help button in a dialog box<\link>
 <item> <link help-browser>Open the Help Manager to browse all the available help<\link>
<\list>

<newline>&empty;
You can also start the AnswerBook Navigator for access to any AnswerBook online 
documentation that may be available to you.  See <xref StartABTA>.

<s1 id=help-key>Help Key
<newline>&empty;<newline>

The quickest and easiest way to get help is to press the F1 key.  When you 
press F1, the application you are using displays the help topic most closely 
related to your current activity.

Some keyboards have a dedicated "Help" key which may take the place of the 
F1 key.

<procedure>More ...
<list bullet tight>
<item> <xref help-menu>
<item> <xref help-button>
<item> <xref help-browser>
<\list>

<s1 id=help-menu>Help Menu
<newline>&empty;<newline>

Most applications have a Help menu for requesting specific kinds of help.

<p gentity=HelpMenu gposition=left>
<term nogloss>Overview<\term> displays introductory information 
about the application<newline>
<term nogloss>Tasks<\term> displays instructions for using the application
<newline><term nogloss>Reference<\term> displays summary information about 
application components  
<newline><term nogloss>On Item<\term> changes the pointer to a question 
mark--click the question mark pointer on an item to display its description
<newline><term nogloss>Using Help<\term> displays information 
about using Help
<newline><term nogloss>About&sigspace;...&sigspace;<\term>displays version 
and copyright information about the application (in this case, Text Editor)

To learn more about using help windows, choose Using Help from an application's 
Help menu.  Or, you can press F1 while using a Help window.

<procedure>See Also 
<list bullet tight>
<item> <xref help-key>
<item> <xref help-button>
<item> <xref help-browser>
<item> <xref WindowMenuTA>
<\list>

<s1 id=help-button>Help Button
<newline>&empty;<newline>

<p gentity=HelpButton gposition=left> If you need help using an application's 
dialog box, click it's Help button. 

In response, the Help Viewer displays information about the dialog box.

<procedure>See Also
<list bullet tight>
<item> <xref help-key>
<item> <xref help-menu>
<item> <xref help-browser>
<\list>

<s1 id=help-browser>Help Manager
<newline>&empty;<newline>

The Help Manager lists all the online help volumes installed on 
your system.
 
<procedure>To Display the Help Manager

<list order>
<item>  Click the Help control in the Front Panel.
<p gentity=fpnlhelp gposition=left><newline>&empty;<newline>
<newline>

The Help Viewer opens, displaying the Help Manager.

<item> Choose the "Common Desktop Environment" topic to
display the list of help volumes for the desktop.

<item> Browse the list of titles. To open a volume, choose its title.
<\list>

<newline>&empty;<newline>
<p gentity=help-control-icon ghyperlink="browser _HOMETOPIC"
 glinktype=JumpNewView gposition=left><newline>To start the Help Manager from 
 here,<newline> 
 click this picture of the Help control. 

<procedure>See Also
<list bullet tight>
<item> <xref help-key>
<item> <xref help-menu>
<item> <xref help-button>
<\list>

<s1 id=StartABTA>Starting the AnswerBook Navigator
	<idx>AnswerBook Navigator: starting<\idx>
	<idx>starting: AnswerBook Navigator<\idx>
<newline>&empty;<newline>

The AnswerBook Navigator lists the contents of your online Library (AnswerBooks that 
have been installed and configured for your use).

<procedure>To Start the AnswerBook Navigator

<list bullet>
<item> <p gentity=ABControl gposition=right>
From the Front Panel:<newline>
<newline>Click the arrow above the Help control in the Front Panel.<newline>
<newline>Then click the AnswerBook control in the Help subpanel.

<item> Or, from the Programs submenu:
 <list order>
 <item> Display the Workspace menu by moving the pointer over the workspace
 backdrop and pressing mouse button 3 on a three-button mouse or mouse
 button 2 on a two-button mouse.

 <item> Drag to choose Programs, then drag to AnswerBook and release the mouse 
 button.
 <\list>
<\list>



